Question:
Arrange the digits from 1 to 9 to make a 9-digit number ABCDEFGHI which satisfies the following conditions:
1) AB is divisible by 2;
2) ABC is divisible by 3;
3) ABCD is divisible by 4;
4) ABCDE is divisible by 5;
5) ABCDEF is divisible by 6;
6) ABCDEFG is divisible by 7;
7) ABCDEFGH is divisible by 8;
8) ABCDEFGHI is divisible by 9.
There is only one solution.

Response:
Let  

• H = “heads”, T = “tails”;  
• a coin is coded 0 if it shows H and 1 if it shows T;  
• k = number of moves that Tom makes;  
• Sₘ  (m = 1,…,k) is the set of the 7 coins he **does not** flip in move m (he flips the other 93).

1.  Parity condition for k  

   If a coin i is not flipped in Sₘ it is flipped in that move, otherwise not.  
   Hence, during k moves

            (# times coin i is flipped) = k – s_i ,

   where s_i = |{m : coin i ∈ Sₘ}| is the number of moves in which coin i is spared.  
   To end up 1 (tails) each coin has to be flipped an odd number of times, so

            k – s_i ≡ 1 (mod 2)  for every i.      (1)

   • If k were odd, (1) would force every s_i to be even.  
     Then ∑ s_i (sum over the 100 coins) would be even, but also

            ∑ s_i = 7k ≡ 7·1 ≡ 1 (mod 2),

     an impossibility.  Therefore k cannot be odd.

   • Thus k is even, and (1) tells us that every s_i must be odd (1,3,5,…,k).

2.  Lower bound for k  

   Because all 100 coins must have s_i ≥ 1 (and odd),

            ∑ s_i ≥ 100·1 = 100.

   But ∑ s_i = 7k, so 7k ≥ 100 ⇒ k ≥ 100/7 ≈ 14.29.  
   With k required to be even, the first admissible value is

            k = 16.

   Hence no sequence of ≤14 moves can work, and 16 is the only possible candidate for the minimum.

3.  Showing that 16 moves are enough  

   We must exhibit 16 sets S₁,…,S₁₆, each of size 7, such that every coin appears in an odd number of them.  
   Choose six “special” coins (label them 1–6) that will appear three times each; the remaining 94 coins will appear exactly once.  
   The row-sum requirements are then

            6·3 + 94·1 = 18 + 94 = 112 = 7·16,

   exactly the total number of “spared–coin slots” available in 16 moves.

   A concrete schedule works as follows (each line lists the 7 coins **left unflipped** in that move):

   S₁  = {1,2,7,8,9,10,11}  
   S₂  = {1,3,12,13,14,15,16}  
   S₃  = {1,4,17,18,19,20,21}  
   S₄  = {2,3,22,23,24,25,26}  
   S₅  = {2,4,27,28,29,30,31}  
   S₆  = {3,4,32,33,34,35,36}  
   S₇  = {5,37,38,39,40,41,42}  
   S₈  = {5,43,44,45,46,47,48}  
   S₉  = {5,49,50,51,52,53,54}  
   S₁₀ = {6,55,56,57,58,59,60}  
   S₁₁ = {6,61,62,63,64,65,66}  
   S₁₂ = {6,67,68,69,70,71,72}  
   S₁₃ = {73,74,75,76,77,78,79}  
   S₁₄ = {80,81,82,83,84,85,86}  
   S₁₅ = {87,88,89,90,91,92,93}  
   S₁₆ = {94,95,96,97,98,99,100}

   • Coins 1–6 each occur in exactly 3 of the Sₘ’s (odd).  
   • Every other coin appears once (odd).  
   • Each Sₘ indeed has 7 distinct coins.

   Therefore after these 16 moves every coin has been flipped an odd number of times, so they all show tails.

4.  Conclusion  

   • k must be even and at least 16;  
   • 16 moves can actually achieve the goal.

Final answer: 16

